    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The irregular bubbling and fissures in your starter are a sign of a complex enzymatic process. When flour is mixed with water, enzymes like amylase and lipase break down the starches into simpler sugars, providing a food source for the wild yeast. As the yeast ferments, enzymes like invertase and glucanase break down the starch granules, releasing glucose and other sugars. This breakdown of starches creates a network of tiny channels and pores, allowing CO2 to escape and creating the characteristic bubbles and fissures in the starter. The physical structure of the starter is essentially a three-dimensional lattice of broken-down starches, yeast cells, and other compounds. This complex network is dynamic, with yeast cells and enzymes constantly interacting and reorganizing the structure.",
